As Martin Williams wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/25/2004 at 07:45:13 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>I have been set the problem in my Maths II Module of my degree to find a general 
solution 
>to determine if a vector and a rectangle intersect in 3D space, and then find the point of 
>intersection. The vector is defined using  two points in space A(x,y,z) and B(x,y,z). The 
>rectangle is defined using four points  P,Q,R,S. These points will *always* form a 
rectangle 
>on a plane, however the plane could be of any orientation.
>
>[Difficulty]
>I have tried to solve the problem my self using different methods, however I can't get 
>anything consistent or neat. A pointer in the right direction would be good!
>
>[Thoughts]
>So far I have come up with one solution which is to look at the 3D world as 3 different 
2D 
>spaces, and model the vector as a line and the rectangle as four lines. The 3 different 2D 
>spaces are the (x,y) the (x,z) and the (y,z) axis of the 3D space. Using straight line 
>geometry, if the vectors line crosses the rectangle in all 3 cases then it must pass 
through 
>the rectangle in 3D space. This is not a very efficient way of solving the problem - it 
>requires solving 12 sets of simultaneous equations! Also it does not give the solution as 
to 
>where the vector intersects the rectangle.

Hello Martin,

If a vector stretches from A to B, then it defines a line.  One might determine if this line 
intersects the rectangle formed by P, Q, R, and S.  And then ldetermine if the point on the 
line lies between A and B.


